article.description: Etan Thomas blocked a potential game-tying layup by Andrei Kirilenko in the Washington Wizards' 91-87 victory over the Utah Jazz on Tuesday night.
article.headline: Wizards' Hughes drops 20 in 4th quarter
article.linkText: Hughes leads Wizards over out-of-tune Jazz
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Complain about the refs, pay a $5,000 fine, and then you'll get the calls. Well, that's one way to look at the Washington Wizards' 91-87 victory over the Utah Jazz on Tuesday. Larry Hughes earned 16 trips to the free-throw line and made 14 of them, two days after coach Eddie Jordan complained that Hughes was treated unfairly in a loss to New York. Hughes finished with a season-high 38 points, including 20 in the fourth quarter. The league announced Tuesday that Jordan had been fined for the remarks he made Sunday, but only after he was given a chance to make his case in a phone call. "Maybe talking to the league this morning might have helped," Jordan said with a chuckle. "That's a side note. I don't want to give the league too much credit." A morning pep talk from owner Abe Pollin also motivated the Wizards, who broke a four-game losing streak. "We're tired of losing streaks," said Hughes, the focal point of the offense with Gilbert Arenas and Jerry Stackhouse both injured. "We don't want losing streaks. We want to fight. We don't want guys coming into our house thinking they're going to win." Hughes shot early and often, making 10 of 21 field goals, including four 3-pointers. He scored Washington's first 13 points of the final quarter and his team's final five points -- all on free throws. And he gave an assist to his coach for sticking up for him with the league. "If that's what it takes," Hughes said. "The coaching staff says they were behind me. They've seen the way I was playing. They thought I was playing the right way and not getting the good end of it, so I respect my coaches for doing it." The Wizards got two critical calls in the final 30 seconds. Etan Thomas blocked a potential game-tying layup by Andrei Kirilenko, and Hughes drew a foul on Greg Ostertag to get two clinching free throws with 3.6 seconds to play. "We have to go home with them shooting all the free throws coming down the stretch," said Utah coach Jerry Sloan, whose team took just two free throws -- compared to Washington's 15 -- in the fourth quarter. "I thought our guys did a good job attacking the basket, but we couldn't come away with what we wanted to be able to come away with." Kirilenko had 17 points and eight rebounds, while Matt Harpring, Carlos Arroyo and Raja Bell had 15 points apiece for the Jazz, who are 1-1 on a six-game road trip. "We're a better team than that," Harpring said. "They're without Arenas tonight, and they beat us. I guess it was just an off night for us." Hughes made up a six-point fourth-quarter deficit by himself, finally getting the lead back for the Wizards with a tough sideways runner that made it 76-75 with 6:15 left. Arroyo and Kirilenko were matching Hughes down the stretch, with Kirilenko's layup pulling the Jazz within one with 2:05 to play. But the Jazz didn't score again, and Thomas' block kept Kirilenko from tying the score with about 20 seconds to play. The Jazz tread a fine line between smooth and ugly for most of the game. An improbable feed into the lane for a layup would be followed by an ill-advised pass in a crowd the next time down. Kirilenko missed all three of his shots in the second quarter, including a breakaway layup with the nearest player 10 feet away. Arroyo led a 13-0 run in the third quarter that gave the Jazz their first lead since 2-0. The Wizards came back to tie late in the third behind Brendan Haywood, who scored six quick points in one of his best offensive spurts in several games. Arroyo's assist to Ben Handlogten for a layup put Utah ahead 67-63 going into the fourth.

Game notes
Jared Jeffries had a career-high 11 rebounds and a season-high 11 points for Washington. ... Stackhouse had an MRI on Monday, but there is still no definitive timetable for his return. At best, the Wizards expect him back in the first half of January, with Arenas perhaps returning by the end of December.
